  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research presented in \"Phase diversity-based wavefront sensing for fluorescence microscopy\" has garnered meaningful academic attention, receiving 21 citations as a preprint and 19 additional citations post-publication in reputable venues such as Optica. This indicates a significant contribution to the field of fluorescence microscopy, demonstrating its relevance and influence.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work authored by Courtney Johnson and colleagues, affiliated with prominent institutions including the University of Chicago and the National Institutes of Health, emphasizes advances in fluorescence microscopy through innovative wavefront sensing techniques. The preprint has made a notable mark within the scientific community, with a total of 21 citations, reflecting its importance and the ongoing interest in this area of research.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Following its successful transition to a formal publication in the journal Optica, this work has continued to impact the field, accumulating 19 citations based on the published version. This trajectory illustrates how the research not only captured initial interest but also sustained its relevance upon peer-reviewed dissemination, showcasing the authors' commitment to sharing impactful scientific findings.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The geographical footprint of this research is noteworthy, as it has drawn citations from top countries such as China and the United States, indicating a broad international interest. This underscores the collaborative nature of contemporary research in fluorescence microscopy, where findings can have global implications for both academic and applied contexts.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the absence of funding agencies does not diminish the significance of the work; rather, it highlights the intrinsic value of the research itself, as it stands independently of external financial support. Additionally, the research exhibits a commitment to scientific stewardship through its proven downstream reuse, facilitating further studies and enhancing the discourse within the community. Ultimately, this research is a testament to the ongoing efforts to push the boundaries of fluorescence microscopy, paving the way for future innovations in imaging technologies.</p>",
